    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Eugenicists relied heavily on the \"intelligence quotient\" (IQ) scores from early 20th‑century mental tests, which they claimed could be measured across racial groups to determine relative cognitive fitness. They also tracked birth rates and mortality statistics, using these demographic data points to calculate a \"fitness index\" that would show which races were reproducing more successfully. In addition to IQ, they focused on physical traits such as cranial capacity, facial features, and stature, arguing that these biological markers were heritable and could be used to rank the superiority of different racial groups. By combining these metrics, eugenicists constructed a seemingly scientific framework that justified their racial hierarchies as both natural and measurable.",
